text: A variety of socioeconomic and cultural factors were identified as major barriers to accessing and utilizing MHCS. Over half of the women surveyed cited poverty, illiteracy, restrictions from their husbands, the distance to health facilities, and long queues as reasons for not using services. Additionally, over a third of the women pointed to cultural practices within their communities as a cause for delays in seeking care. These findings reveal that addressing maternal health in this region requires more than just improving clinical services; it also means tackling deeply rooted societal and personal challenges that women face daily.
translated: [Ekoti mingi ya masomo ya jamii na ya kitamaduni elingiwa kama vizuizi vikuu kwa kupata na kutumia MHCS. Zaidi ya nusu ya wanawake waliohojiwa walisema umaskini, ujuzi usio na elimu, vikwazo kutoka kwa waume wao, umbali wa vituo vya afya, na mizunguko ndefu kama sababu za kutotumia huduma. Zaidi ya hayo, zaidi ya theluthi moja ya wanawake walitaja mazoea ya kitamaduni ndani ya jamii zao kama sababu ya kusubiri kupata huduma. Matokeo haya yanafichua kwamba kushughulikia afya ya uzazi katika eneo hili kunahitaji zaidi ya kuboresha tu huduma za kimatibabu; pia ina maana ya kushughulikia changamoto za kijamii na za kibinafsi zilizo na mizizi kwa kina ambazo wanawake hukabiliana kila siku.]
backtranslated: [Most social and cultural studies identified as major barriers to access to and use of MHCS. More than half of the women surveyed cited poverty, lack of education, barriers from their husbands, lack of health facilities, and long cycles as reasons for not using services. Additionally, more than one-third of women cited cultural practices within their communities as reasons for waiting to access services. These results suggest that addressing reproductive health in this area requires more than just improving basic medical services; it also requires addressing the underlying social and personal challenges that women face on a daily basis.]

text: Despite his shortcomings, Unoka was a talented musician. He was a tall but very thin man with a slight stoop and a mournful look, which would disappear when he was drinking or playing his flute. His happiest moments came in the months after the harvest, when the village musicians would retrieve their instruments from above the fireplace. Unoka would join them, his face filled with pure joy and peace. Sometimes, other villages would invite Unoka and his band to teach them their tunes, and they would stay for several months, sharing their music.
translated: [Ndakisa ya makambo yake, Unoka alikuwa mwimbaji mwenye talanta. Alikuwa mtu mrefu lakini mnyembamba sana na kipunguzo kidogo na uso wa kuhuzunika, ambao ungepotea wakati akiwa anakunywa au akicheza filimbi yake. Muda wake wa furaha zaidi ulikuwa katika miezi baada ya mavuno, wakati wanamuziki wa kijiji wangechukua ala zao za muziki kutoka juu ya kivuli cha moto. Unoka alijiunga nao, uso wake ukijaa furaha na amani. Mara nyingi, vijiji vingine vilimwita Unoka na bendi yake kufundisha nyimbo zao, na walibaki kwa miezi kadhaa, kushiriki muziki wao.]
backtranslated: [A case in point, Unoka was a talented singer. He was a tall but very thin man with a slight discount on the sad face, which would be lost when he was drinking or playing his fiddle. His happiest time was in the months after the harvest, when the village musicians would pick up their instruments from the top of the fire shade. Unoka joined them, his face filled with joy and happiness. Often, other villages invited Unoka and his band to teach their songs, and he stayed for several months, sharing their music.]

text: At the Derby Avenue RC Basic School and St. Georgeâ€™s Anglican Basic School in Accra, invigilators were captured openly demanding GHÂ¢60 daily tokens, supervisors pocketed envelopes of GHÂ¢400, and candidates were asked to contribute to an Aseda Offertory. John Kapi stressed that once WAEC provides feedback on such incidents, it is the responsibility of the Ghana Education Service (GES) to take decisive action. And so when these issues come up, once the feedback goes to them, we [WAEC] expect that they would react appropriately and ensure that the right action is taken against the people, he said.
translated: [Ni kati ya shule ya msingi ya Derby Avenue RC na shule ya msingi ya St. Georgeâ€™s Anglican huko Accra, watu wanaosimamia mtihani waliwekwa kwenye kamera wakidai waziwazi tokeni za kila siku za GHÂ¢60, wasimamizi walipata mifuko ya GHÂ¢400, na wanafunzi waliombwa kuchangia Aseda Offertory. John Kapi alisisitiza kwamba mara WAEC itatoa maoni kuhusu matukio kama hayo, ni wajibu wa Huduma ya Elimu ya Ghana (GES) kuchukua hatua za haraka. Na kwa hivyo wakati masuala haya yanapotokea, mara maoni yanapowasilishwa kwao, tuna [WAEC] matarajio kwamba watajibu ipasavyo na kuhakikisha kwamba hatua sahihi inachukuliwa dhidi ya watu hao, alisema.]
backtranslated: [In Derby Avenue RC Primary School and St. George's Anglican Primary School in Accra, the examination administrators were caught on camera openly demanding daily GHÂ¢60 tokens, administrators were given GHÂ¢400 bags, and students were asked to contribute to the Aseda Offertory. John Kapi stressed that as soon as WAEC issues a statement regarding such incidents, it is the responsibility of the Ghana Education Service (GES) to take immediate action. Therefore, when issues arise, as soon as the statement is submitted to them, we expect [WAEC] to respond appropriately and ensure that appropriate action is taken against such people, he said.]

text: For rural communities in Ghana, especially in the Kumbungu district, access to and use of maternal healthcare services (MHCS) remain a significant challenge. This study set out to explore the specific barriers preventing women from utilizing these services and to evaluate the quality of care provided. The research adopted a mixed-methods approach, combining both quantitative and qualitative data to get a comprehensive view of the situation. This phased design involved surveying 441 pregnant and postpartum women and conducting interviews with 20 healthcare providers. A facility checklist was also used to assess the state of clinics, including the availability of essential drugs and equipment.

text: Okonkwo was a man of great renown throughout his nine villages and even beyond, a fame built entirely on his own remarkable achievements. At just eighteen years old, he brought honor to his village by defeating Amalinze the Cat, a legendary wrestler who had been undefeated for seven years. Amalinze earned his nickname because his back never once touched the earth. The old men of the village considered Okonkwo's victory one of the fiercest fights they had ever seen.

text: The study also shed light on significant facility-based challenges that compromise the quality of care. A key issue was the inadequate number of midwives, which likely contributes to the long queues women reported. Additionally, the absence of essential equipment and drugs was a major problem. For example, health service providers specifically recommended a greater number of trained midwives and the provision of critical logistics like ultrasound machines and proper delivery equipment to ensure effective and high-quality care.

text: Okonkwo was an imposing figure, tall and massive with a severe expression, a result of his bushy eyebrows and wide nose. His breathing was so heavy that his family could hear it from their own houses when he slept. When he walked, his heels barely touched the ground, making him seem poised to pounce on someoneâ€”which he often did. He had a slight stammer, and in moments of anger, he would resort to his fists when words failed him. He had no patience for men who were not successful, and this sentiment stemmed from his deep-seated shame for his own father.

text: The study found that while a high percentage of women did engage with some maternal health servicesâ€”87.5% attended antenatal care (ANC), 87.3% had a skilled delivery, and 84.8% had a postnatal care (PNC) visitâ€”the frequency of care was a concern. A little over half of the participants (53.4%) had the recommended four or more ANC visits, and nearly half (46.9%) didn't register until their second trimester. These figures highlight a gap between initial access and consistent, timely utilization of services, suggesting that women may be facing obstacles that prevent them from fully engaging with the healthcare system throughout their pregnancies.

text: The crowd held its breath as the drums beat and the flutes sang. Amalinze was a clever opponent, but Okonkwo was just as skilled, and as slippery as a fish in water. Both men were incredibly strong, their muscles and nerves straining to the point of almost breaking. But in the end, Okonkwo emerged victorious. This monumental win was just the beginning of his legacy. Over the next twenty years, his fame spread like a wildfire, fueled by his unwavering resolve and personal triumphs.

Wanachama wengine wa kamati hii ni Alhaji Collins Dauda (MP na mwenyekiti wa Kamati ya Ardhi na Maliasili katika Bunge), Padri Lazarus Annyere (Mwenyekiti wa Baraza la Amani la Mkoa wa Savannah), Dk. Festus Aubyn (Mtandao wa Kusimamia Amani katika Afrika ya Magharibi), Sylvia Hormane Noagbesenu Esq (Mkurugenzi wa Muda wa Taasisi ya Wanawake, Vijana, Amani na Usalama, Kituo cha Mafunzo ya Kulinda Amani cha Kimataifa cha Kofi Annan), Profesa Ramatu Alhassan na Dk. George Amoh (Katibu wa NPC) ambaye atakuwa katibu.]
backtranslated: [The seven-member Interim Committee will be chaired by Mr. Emmanuel Habuka Bombande. Other members of this committee are Alhaji Collins Dauda (MP and Chairman of the Ardhi and Maliasili Committee in Parliament), Father Lazarus Annyere (Chairman of the Savannah Regional Peace Council), Dr. Festus Aubyn (Peacebuilding Network in West Africa), Sylvia Hormane Noagbesenu Esq (Interim Director of the Institute for Women, Youth, Peace and Security, Kofi Annan International Peacebuilding Training Centre), Professor Ramatu Alhassan and Dr. George Amoh (Chairman of the NPC) who will be the members.]

text: To improve maternal health in the Kumbungu district, both study participants and service providers offered actionable recommendations. Women suggested focusing on public education about maternal care, enforcing free MHCS, and improving the local road network to make facilities more accessible. Providers emphasized the need for more midwives and better equipment. The study concludes that both governmental and non-governmental organizations must increase investment in maternal health and address the broader socioeconomic issues affecting women. This comprehensive approach, tackling both healthcare system deficiencies and community-level barriers, is essential for truly improving maternal health outcomes.

text: Unoka, Okonkwo's father, had passed away ten years prior. He was a man known for his laziness and carelessness, living only for the present with no thought for the future. Any money he managed to acquireâ€”which was a rare occurrenceâ€”he would immediately spend on palm-wine, gathering his neighbors for a celebration. He believed that to see a dead man's mouth was to see the foolishness of not eating what you had in life. Unoka was also deeply in debt, owing money to nearly every one of his neighbors.
translated: [Unoka, tata ya Okonkwo, alikufa miaka kumi iliyopita. Alikuwa mtu anayejulikana kwa uvivu wake na usio na uangalifu, akiishi tu kwa ajili ya sasa bila kufikiria kuhusu siku zijazo. Fedha yoyote aliyoweza kupataâ€”jambo ambalo halikuwa na kawaidaâ€”alitumia mara moja kwa ajili ya pombe ya mafuta ya mawese, akiwaleta majirani wake kwa ajili ya sherehe. Aliamini kwamba kuona mdomo wa mtu aliyekufa ni kuona ujinga wa kutokula kile ulichonacho maishani. Unoka pia alikuwa na deni kubwa, akidaiwa na watu wengi wa majirani yake.]
backtranslated: [Unoka, Okonkwo's father, died ten years ago. He was a man known for his laziness and carelessness, living only for the present without thinking about the future. Any money he could find - a word that was unusual - he used immediately for palm oil liquor, bringing his neighbors for the feast. He believed that seeing the dead man's food was to see the folly of eating what you see in life. Unoka also had a large debt, he was hated by most of his neighbors.]
